          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The disease remits after withdrawal of the offending drug</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In evaluating a patient with a suspected diagnosis of drug-induced lupus erythematosus (DILE), which of the following statements is INCORRECT?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2833636",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31881,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Anti histone antibody levels are low</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Anti-histone antibody levels are low:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This statement is<strong> incorrect</strong>. In DILE, there is typically a<strong> high level of anti-histone antibodies, </strong>which is a<strong> hallmark of the condition </strong>and helps differentiate it from <strong>idiopathic SLE</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Affects males and females equally:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> DILE does not demonstrate the same <strong>female predominance </strong>as systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). Both males and females are affected equally.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Renal and CNS involvement is uncommon:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Unlike SLE, DILE typically <strong>spares the kidneys and central nervous system</strong>, with these organ systems being less commonly involved.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: The disease remits after withdrawal of the offending drug:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> One of the key features of <strong>DILE </strong>is that symptoms usually resolve upon <strong>withdrawal of the offending drug</strong>, differentiating it from<strong> idiopathic SLE</strong>, which is a chronic condition.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Drug-induced lupus erythematosus </strong>is characterized by <strong>high levels of anti-histone antibodies</strong>, and unlike<strong> idiopathic SLE</strong>, it affects <strong>males and females equally, renal and CNS involvement are uncommon</strong>, and the condition usually remits after<strong> withdrawal of the offending drug</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Reference Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/229</span></strong></span></span></p>",
