        },
        {
          "id": 56760,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Neutrophil </span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In the context of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), which cell type is historically known for its role in the formation of lupus erythematosus (LE) cells, a phenomenon once used in the diagnosis of SLE?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3489530",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31880,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Neutrophil</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>lupus erythematosus (LE) cell </strong>is a phagocytic<strong> neutrophil or macrophage.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Nuclei of damaged cells </strong>react with <strong>ANAs, lose their chromatin pattern</strong>, and become <strong>homogeneous </strong>to produce<strong> LE bodies or hematoxylin bodies. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Phagocytic neutrophils or macrophages engulf the denatured nucleus </strong>of an injured cell. Demonstration of <strong>LE cells in vitro </strong>was used in the <strong>past for the diagnosis of SLE.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Neutrophil:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> The<strong> LE cell is a neutrophil</strong> that has<strong> phagocytosed the denatured nucleus of another cell</strong>, which is a characteristic feature seen in<strong> SLE.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Lymphocyte:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Lymphocytes are primarily involved in <strong>adaptive immune responses </strong>and are <strong>not typically phagocytic cells </strong>associated with the <strong>formation of LE cells.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Endothelial Cell:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Endothelial cells line <strong>blood vessels </strong>and are<strong> not involved in phagocytosis or the formation of LE cells</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Eosinophil:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Eosinophils are involved in <strong>allergic reactions and parasitic infections </strong>and do not form LE cells.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>LE cells are neutrophils or macrophages </strong>that have <strong>phagocytosed nuclear material</strong>. The demonstration of<strong> LE cells </strong>used to be a <strong>diagnostic test for SLE</strong>, reflecting the <strong>autoantibody-mediated destruction of cells </strong>leading to the presentation of <strong>nuclear antigens to these phagocytes. </strong></span></span></p>",
