          "id": 56655,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Expressing sequestrated antigens </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 56656,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Antigenic cross reactivity </span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In a patient with Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection presenting with symptoms of autoimmunity, which mechanism is most likely contributing to the production of autoantibodies?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5493864",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31882,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B)</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Polyclonal B cell activation </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Polyclonal B cell activation is caused by<strong> EBV and HIV </strong>resulting in production of <strong>autoantibodies. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Polyclonal B cell activation:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> EBV infection </strong>is associated with <strong>polyclonal B cell activation. </strong>This uncontrolled activation can lead to the production of a<strong> wide array of antibodies, </strong>including <strong>autoantibodies.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Molecular Mimicry:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Molecular mimicry involves an<strong> infectious agent </strong>sharing <strong>epitopes </strong>with the host, leading to an <strong>immune response </strong>that <strong>cross-reacts with self-tissues. </strong>It is a known mechanism in certain <strong>autoimmune diseases </strong>but is not<strong> the primary mechanism </strong>by which <strong>EBV induces autoimmunity</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Expressing sequestrated antigens:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Sequestered antigens, normally hidden from the<strong> immune system,</strong> may become exposed due to t<strong>issue damage or other pathological processes</strong>, which could induce an <strong>autoimmune response.</strong> However, this is not typically associated with EBV infection.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: Antigenic Cross-reactivity:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Antigenic cross-reactivity refers to an <strong>immune response against one antigen </strong>that reacts with a different but <strong>structurally similar antigen</strong>. While it can contribute to <strong>autoimmunity, </strong>it is not the primary process implicated in EBV-related autoimmunity.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The development of <strong>autoimmunity </strong>in the context of <strong>EBV infection </strong>is primarily associated with <strong>polyclonal B cell activation</strong>, leading to the production of <strong>autoantibodies. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><em><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">(Ref: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup> 220) </span></span></em></strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><em> </em></strong></span></span></p>",
