      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">14-year-old girl experiences episodes of pallor, pain, and cyanosis in her extremities upon exposure to cold. This condition often precedes the development of which systemic disease, known for its cutaneous manifestations and association with such vascular phenomena?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5103383",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31883,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Scleroderma </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Scleroderma (Systemic Sclerosis):</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Scleroderma is well known for <strong>skin thickening and Raynaud&#39;s phenomenon, </strong>which is seen in virtually all patients and often precedes other symptoms, making it the most likely diagnosis associated with these symptoms.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE):</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> SLE is a <strong>chronic autoimmune disease </strong>with various clinical presentations,<strong> including Raynaud&#39;s phenomenon</strong>. However, SLE is characterized more by <strong>systemic symptoms </strong>and<strong> less by the cutaneous changes described.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA):</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> RA is a <strong>chronic inflammatory disease </strong>primarily affecting the <strong>joints. </strong>While vascular symptoms can occur, they are <strong>not as prominent </strong>as the <strong>articular manifestations </strong>and not typically preceded by Raynaud&#39;s phenomenon.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: Histiocytosis:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Histiocytosis refers to a <strong>group of disorders </strong>characterized by the <strong>proliferation of histiocytes</strong>. It <strong>does not commonly </strong>present with<strong> Raynaud&#39;s phenomenon </strong>as an initial symptom.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Raynaud&#39;s phenomenon</strong>, characterized by episodic<strong> vasoconstriction of the arteries and arterioles of the extremities</strong>, is commonly associated with <strong>scleroderma </strong>and can precede <strong>other symptoms of the disease</strong>.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><em><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">(Ref: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 228-229) </span></span></em></strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><em><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></em></strong></span></span></p>",
