          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">NOD like receptor</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A patient presents with chronic nonmalignant lymphoproliferation, autoimmune cytopenias, and a family history suggestive of a genetic syndrome. Genetic testing for which of the following genes is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5572089",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31877,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) FAS</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Self-reactive B cells </strong>are killed by<strong> Fas L on T cells engaging Fas on the B </strong>cells. Mutations in<strong> Fas or Fas L in mice and humans result in an autoimmune disease </strong>reminiscent of <strong>human SLE </strong>called the <strong><em>autoimmune lymphoproliferative syndrome (ALPS)</em></strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">FAS:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> The FAS gene encodes a <strong>cell surface receptor </strong>important for the <strong>apoptotic death of cells</strong>, including <strong>self-reactive B and T lymphocytes</strong>. Mutations in the FAS gene can<strong> lead to ALPS, </strong>characterized by accumulation of<strong> lymphocytes and increased risk of autoimmune disease.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: PTPN22:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> The PTPN22 gene encodes a<strong> tyrosine phosphatase involved in T cell receptor signaling. </strong>Mutations in this gene are associated with various autoimmune conditions, such as <strong>rheumatoid arthritis and type 1 diabetes</strong>, but not typically with <strong>autoimmune lymphoproliferative syndrome (ALPS).</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: FADD:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> FADD is an <strong>adaptor protein </strong>involved in the <strong>apoptotic pathway</strong>. While important for <strong>apoptosis</strong>, known mutations in FADD are not classically associated with ALPS.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: NOD-like Receptor:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> NOD-like receptors are <strong>intracellular sensors of microbial motifs </strong>and<strong> cell stress </strong>that lead to <strong>inflammation, not apoptosis. </strong>Mutations in <strong>NOD-like receptors </strong>are associated with <strong>autoinflammatory syndromes, not ALPS.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Autoimmune lymphoproliferative syndrome (ALPS) </strong>is often caused by <strong>mutations in the FAS gene</strong>, which leads to defects in the <strong>apoptotic pathway, </strong>specifically in the <strong>programmed cell death of lymphocytes</strong>. This condition is characterized by<strong> autoimmune manifestations similar to systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).</strong></span></span></p>",
