      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 26-year-old female presents with complaints of fatigue since 2 months. She has persistent arthralgia of the distal and proximal interphalangeal joints of both hands. Her physical examination is normal and there is no tenderness or deformity of the joints of the hands. A complete blood count is normal and her antinuclear antibody titer is elevated at 1:90. Which of the following additional tests would confirm the diagnosis of lupus erythematosus?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2855352",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31879,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Positive anti-Smith antibody</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Anti-Smith </strong>(B) is<strong> most specific</strong> for <strong>systemic lupus</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Positive anti-Smith antibody:</strong> The anti-Smith antibody is<strong> highly specific for SLE</strong>. This<strong> and a positive ANA </strong>would strongly support the<strong> diagnosis of SLE.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A: Positive SS-A:</strong> SS-A (or Ro) antibodies are associated with <strong>SLE </strong>(presence of the other issues like subacute cutaneous lupus)<strong> and Sjögren’s syndrome. </strong>Although they can be present in SLE, they are <strong>not specific to </strong>it, especially when considering the patient's clinical presentation.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C: Positive anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide (CCP-IgG):</strong> Anti-CCP IgG is<strong> highly specific for rheumatoid arthritis </strong>and is not typically used in the diagnosis of SLE.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D: Positive rheumatoid factor:</strong> Rheumatoid factor can be positive in a variety of<strong> rheumatologic diseases, including SLE</strong>, but it is <strong>not specific for SLE </strong>and is <strong>more commonly associated with rheumatoid arthritis.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">When evaluating a patient for SLE, the <strong>anti-Smith antibody test is the most specific serological test </strong>and can <strong>confirm the diagnosis </strong>when the clinical picture is suggestive of the disease.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">ANA = screen → very sensitive but non-specific.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Anti-Smith antibody - highly specific for SLE → confirms diagnosis when present.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Anti-dsDNA is also specific and associated with lupus nephritis, but among the choices given, anti-Smith is the classic confirmatory antibody.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 222</strong></span></p>",
